<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="293" pageId="3" pageNumber="292" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[199,1436,1994,2021]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="293" pageId="3" pageNumber="292">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1994,2020]" pageId="3" pageNumber="292">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Pérez-Flores, 2022" authorityName="Pérez-Flores" authorityYear="2022" box="[321,553,1994,2020]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="292" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tlaxcalaensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[321,553,1994,2020]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="292">Methia tlaxcalaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[559,648,1994,2020]" pageId="3" pageNumber="292">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[559,648,1994,2020]" pageId="3" pageNumber="292" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[662,729,1994,2020]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1852,1876]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,560,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-151@3.[151,1436,560,1828]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. A–D) Methia tlaxcalaensis sp. nov. holotype female: A) Dorsal habitus; B) Ventral habitus C) Lateral habitus; D) Head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673534/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="292">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) is easily distinguished from congeners by the elytra length and elytral integument pattern, with three diffuse whitish-brown maculae. 
<taxonomicName authority="Pérez-Flores, 2022" authorityName="Pérez-Flores" authorityYear="2022" box="[933,1165,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tlaxcalaensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[933,1165,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">Methia tlaxcalaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1172,1261,151,177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1172,1261,151,177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Chemsak &amp; Linsley, 1964" authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Linsley" authorityYear="1964" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[1406,1429,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,223,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">vittata</emphasis>
Chemsak &amp; Linsley, 1964
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Chemsak &amp; Linsley, 1964" authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Linsley" authorityYear="1964" box="[577,1025,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subvittata">
<emphasis box="[577,600,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[615,725,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">subvittata</emphasis>
Chemsak &amp; Linsley, 1964
</taxonomicName>
but differs by the elytral integument pattern, with longitudinal vittae in these last two. Also, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Linsley" authorityYear="1964" box="[795,904,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[795,818,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[832,904,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chemsak &amp; Linsley" authorityYear="1964" box="[957,1103,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subvittata">
<emphasis box="[957,980,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[993,1103,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">subvittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the elytra surpassing the ventrites in length, in 
<taxonomicName authority="Pérez-Flores, 2022" authorityName="Pérez-Flores" authorityYear="2022" box="[356,588,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tlaxcalaensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[356,588,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">Methia tlaxcalaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[595,685,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="293">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[595,685,259,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="293" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
the elytra reach the middle of ventrite V.
</paragraph>
